- VSCode Version: 1.3.1
- OS Version: OSX El Capitan 10.11.6

Steps to Reproduce:
tab size = 4 spaces
write the following code in vscode and press alt+shift+f, next statement after `try` i.e `var connection = mysql.createConnection({` should have 4 spaces 

> var fs = require('fs');
> var mysql = require('mysql');
> 
> try {
>   var connection = mysql.createConnection({
>     host: '127.0.0.1',
>     user: 'root',
>     password: 'root',
>     database: 'test'
>   });
> 
>   connection.connect(function(err) {
>     if (err) {
>       throw err;
>     }
> 
> connection.query(
>         'SELECT 1', function(err, nRows) {
>           if (err) {
>             throw err;
>           }
>           console.log(nRows);
>         })
> connection.end(function(err) {
>       if (err) throw err;
>     })
> 
> })
> } catch (error) {
>   console.log(error);
> }

- VSCode Version: 1.3.1
- OS Version: Windows 7 x64

Currently vscode supports CTRL-clicking links and/or classes in imports to open said file (and clicking certain things to go to the definition, but that's not the point here).
`import {NKDatetime} from '../../lib/ng2-datetime/ng2-datetime';`

If we have an identical definition that's not part of an import statement, CTRL-clicking doesn't work.

```
class Test {
    a = '../../lib/ng2-datetime/ng2-datetime';
}
```

This is probably because it's not clear what the string is supposed to be and therefore it was never added.

The proposal:
If a string is clicked with CTRL as a modifier and the string has a known file ending, vscode should attempt to open the file.

The primary use case that I encountered is opening template files in Angular 2.

```
@Component({
    selector: 'editor',
    templateUrl: 'views/editor.html',
})
```
